Up by 4 points averages over 6 polls. Std. Error is about 4 in each, averages probably about 2 in the aggregate for a standard error. Chance Kasich is 2 points lower or more is about 15%. If he goes down 2 points, Trump probably goes up by most of 2%, but probably not quite enough to win. So call it 10% chance Trump is really in the lead and polls are sampling wrong. Kasich is very well known in Ohio, so late breakers should already know if they want to vote for him. Same issue with Trump, I think he does not do well with late breakers. Lastly, Kasich has momentum so this may mean late breakers side with him. Trump weekend kerfuffle probably makes him weaker and polls may have missed some of that. Bump Kasich up a little, but I'm disinclined to go much above 90, especially given polling errors in Michigan, so I'll stay at 90 or maybe even move down a little. 1% for Cruze seems too generous, but then I remember the Michigan polling disaster.

This is a really tough one. Looking at the RCP polls, Kasich's lead seems pretty anemic. For a guy who won every county but one in his last race for governor, he should be doing a lot better. I think the problem is immigration, and his stance on the "path to legalization." Immigration is the big issue for the Republicans this year, and a great ground game and statewide organization is a handicap if you have taken a position that's at odds with the majority of voters. Kasich's outreach is just telling people that he believes in a policy that most of them disagree with. I think it will be close, but I think Trump will win. People will vote their rust-belt economic interests and their white working class ethnic demographic interests, both of which Trump plays to.

The current consensus forecast is that there is a 21% chance that either Cruz or Rubio will win Ohio. But it's certainly time (for me, at any rate) to dispense with the fiction that either Cruz or Rubio has a chance worthy of the name. The polls have never favored either in this state, and they now project a less than 1% chance that either will win[a]. Furthermore, neither Rubio nor Cruz have especially interesting advantages in Ohio (i.e., they don't hold elected office there, they weren't born there, they haven't lived there or gone to university there, they don't run businesses that have large interests there, etc.), and Rubio has even told his supporters to vote for Kasich[b]!

It feels like a bit of a mug's game, trying to forecast this one. Kasich has closed with Trump in the polls in the last few days[1], and he (i.e., Kasich) has been a rather popular governor in this state[2]. Rubio's endorsement (if that's the word I'm looking for) might help Kasich a bit too[3]. The party establishment seems to be making more than a nominal effort on Kasich's behalf[4], though - honestly - that's not proved to be of much value so far. However, a new PAC-based anti-Trump add running in Ohio right now does look like it might have some impact[5]. If Trump has anything (other than consistently good polling numbers!) in his favor, it's the possibility of crossover Democrats voting for him[6]. We probably won't have much of a sense of whether they'll make an impact (or even materialize) until the exit poll data starts rolling in.

John Kasich, a popular two term governor of the state, has strong structural advantages going into his state's primary. However, Kasich is a relative moderate, and the closed primary may benefit more hard-line registered Republicans who are more likely to turn out for the primary election.
